There was a question on here yesterday about getting over lower back pain that comes from slacklining. Wanted to drop this here for everyone‚Äôs reference. 

This exercise is called the seated good morning, you can do it with weight (barbell) or without weight. I‚Äôd highly recommend doing this with weight once you‚Äôre comfortable. Not only will that increase the stretch at the bottom of the movement, but it also strengthens your muscles throughout the entire range of motion, which is incredibly important for all realms of athleticism, but even more so for slack/highline which puts a lot of strain on your lower back. Pair this with some other cardio cross training, and strength and mobility work and my lower back pain when slacking no longer exists. Bonus points if you start training Nordic curls as well (hamstring curl machine works too, but nordics are an incredible workout for lower back strength).

Disclaimer: so much in the exercise space is purely anecdotal. I‚Äôm sharing what has worked for me and my body. I hope it works for you as well.

text:
HiüòÄ
Yesterday I spent 12 hours walking on slackline. No fall, no sitting, no touching the ground. Here are few tips if you ever want to try it.
1. Learn to walk with your toes pointing inwards (the same way as Sascha Grill - Slackliner walks speedlines). The biggest pain I felt were my ankles. You can get them in different position and relieve some pain.
2. Don't look at time too often otherwise the time will pass very slowly.
3.Don't have a goal of staying there for some amount of hours. Try to stay there until you fall. It feels much better when you don't know how long will it take.
4.Be ok with falling. You can try it again next time. The worst thing is to be nervous about it. Then it feels like forever.

Last year I spent 10 hours on 2,5 cm webbing with shoes. This time I used 5 cm trickline webbing with barefoot shoes. I thought it will be better but it was the same. I could never do it barefoot on 2,5 cm webbing.

I hope to see some of you try itüòÄ

topComments.name: Mat Bolduc
topComments.text:
I‚Äôve been working through a lower back injury for the past year and a half and have finally recovered. Firstly, the gym is your best friend. I did a ton of core and back strengthening exercises. 

I now do a set of simple warm up stretches before every session. Childs pose, Childs pose to the left and right, cat cow, downward dog, three leg dog, warrior into warrior 3 then end with forward folds. 

Lastly, I started using a big wall harness with loads of padding which has been extremely beneficial for taking tons of whips during freestyle sessions

Split details:

Rig: 00:12:00
Slack: 1:09:12  AVG: 1 hr 9min/mi
derig/transition: 00:20:00

T3: 00:14:21
Run: 01:48:23  AVG: 8:16 min/mi

Total Triathlon Time: 6:07:59

Line was 30-35 M Mantra, very tight. 
Rules for slackline: Walking tree to tree, when I fell off I had to start again right at that spot, no distance tracked for walking back to anchor or anything.

Had my friend and dad bike (no drafting) and run with me. 

Had to swim in a friends pool, 40 ft pool at 160 laps in a thunder rain storm. Half of the bike was in nuking rain/thunder storm. 
Honestly it was a really fun day and not that hard until the second half of the half marathon.

Slack: Mids good at slacking
Swim: Never swam for distance in my life
Bike: Havent biked over 35 miles in 6ish years
Run: Medium to good run fitness

Great time! 7/10 recommend! 

Also: did this 10 months after an L1 burst fracture. GET OUT THERE!

text:
Hello,

It's been a while since we had a proper thunder and (en)lightning conversation, so let's break the silence. 

Last week, we rigged a highline between two hills, 870 meters long at about 1100 meters above sea level. The line was up for about 5 days and, during that time, it got caught in at least three heavy overnight thunderstorms. After we took it down, we checked the setup and found two small burned areas close together. The patches with the raed logo were melted together, and there were some burned holes in them, along with a burned tape and tiny burn marks on the main soft shackle. This was all under an intact layer of tape that hadn't been burned or damaged in any way.

**Weather**

The wind was pretty chill (a steady 2-6 m/s, with peaks up to 16 m/s), but there was a ton of rain (56 mm in 4 days) and some serious thunder. We monitored the forces on the highline, and the peak value was around 6-7 kN. After the thunderstorms, we checked the line on the roller and found no visible issues (we're still not sure which thunderstorm caused the burns).

**Anchors & Materials:**

Both anchor points were essentially big metal constructions sitting on top of the mountains ‚Äî one was the end of a suspension bridge (a 20-meter high steel beam structure), and the other was a skywalk (a big metal viewpoint). The webbing was composed of 9 segments of DynPro + Pulsar, connected with 4mm softies on the main line and 6mm for the backup. 

One or two of the connections were taped differently than the others, with many layers of tape covering all the connection. Other connections were visible, with tape only to secure the knot in place.

**Damage**

I compared the damaged areas (see pictures) with pictures of Samuel Vollery's line after it got hit by lightning (see here https://www.facebook.com/groups/slackchat/permalink/902419289831949/)  and saw similar burn patterns (burned holes). Our best theory is that an electrical discharge (either lightning from storms or a discharge between the two metal constructions used as anchors) ran through the wet line, heating the dry places under the excessive amount of tape (which have higher resistance then) enough to burn and melt the tape, raed stickers, knot of the softshackle and small part of a sewn loop sleeve.

**Conclusion**

What's really concerning is that the outermost layer of tape was intact, so there were no visible burn marks until the first layer was removed. Since the burn marks were really small and probably didn't compromise the strength of the soft shackles and webbing, no one got hurt. We had many successful sends and crossings after the thunderstorms. However, the potential consequences could have been severe, and we're all really happy that nobody got hurt.

There are still many questions up in the air. What exactly happened? Could it have been prevented? Should we derig the line after every thunderstorm to check it, and is that even feasible for longer lines? Does the type and amount of tape make a difference in conducting moisture and resistance...? 

Has something similar happened to you? Feel free to share your stories. Stay safe! ü•≥

topComments.name: Asa Webb
topComments.text: It‚Äôs definitely considered bad practice to use an aluminum biner as a backup connecter when highlining. Some would say aluminum biners don‚Äôt belong on a highline rig at all, I personally use them to clip off tails of weblocks for weblock tie offs and soft release tie offs. That being said I do see your reasoning as you are right it will not see cyclic loading and is only loaded in an emergency scenario, however if your main line breaks for whatever reason I would want to have an anchor that is equally as strong or stronger than my main connector so I‚Äôm not thinking twice about whether or not it‚Äôs strong enough to hold a shock load. I could see this being used in an alpine scenario to save weight but I think there‚Äôs better ways to go lighter.

Hi everyone, I was wondering in which case is it not possible to tandem a line without damage it ?
I don't t tandem myself but a lot of my mates do on my gears (among other things). I have no doubt about the anchors resistance (spansets, steel shackles, etc ...) but I was wondering if there is a case where it's not good for the line to get a hard  tandem leash fall.

For exemple I already did.
-100 meters  feather pro (bc) tandem session

-55 meters Samurai (eqb) tandem session
-52 meters pink tube (slacktivity) tandem session

Are these configurations all ok (I think yes, but It's better to debate about it) ? 
I guess more the line is long and skretchy, more tandem the line is ok.

But what about if I set one of this line shorter ? What about WLL ? What about peak force during a tandem leash fall ?

Tell me what you think, very curious about this question.

topComments.text:
Since there are many mentions of cams in here: cams are not a very suitable anchor device for highlines, unless you know *very* well what you‚Äòre doing. 
Cams have failed highliners several times. They tend to move from the cyclic loads and the movements of typical highline anchors can easily make them slide out of their initial placement. 
Any trad anchor that sees highline loads needs to be extremely well dressed, even with tricams or nuts - since they‚Äôre also known to slip out of their placements from weird loads that often occur in highlines. So if there‚Äòs an option to span the placements in opposite directions, this could improve the anchor by several levels. 
I hope this info helps a bit. Keep the balance :)

text:
Alright, time for a discussion on everyones favorite topic, PERMARIGS?!?! üéâü•≥

3 complete rigs were recently stolen from a local area in the front range. To give some context on the area, it is a popular running and mountain biking location that sees a lot of traffic. This location started as a lowkey spot where an older local set up a line for himself to get away from the madness. He set his line up lower down in the wash a little further from the trail. A couple people found out about this area and it became a freestyle training ground, Not for aesthetic or beauty, solely convenience. 

The hike is 5 minutes into a wash, the current lines are all directly next to a popular mountain biking and hiking trail, or go over it and the exposure is minimal. Fast forward a bit and word got out about ‚Äúhighlines‚Äù that were easy to get to with next to no exposure and you could leave them up for months at a time and the entirety of BoCo was all over it. Moving forward there has pretty much always been at least one line rigged there for the last few years. That area doesn‚Äôt go long without seeing a permarig and is usually permarigged for weeks or months at a time. When I have talked to law enforcement surrounding permarigged lines it‚Äôs often treated like camping gear, 14 days max and then you have to move a minimum distance away. The idea of this practice minimizing impact in areas kinda goes out the window when the rig being taken down is just immediately swapped with another rig. We all know that this community as a whole can be a pretty rowdy bunch at anchors, juggling, playing music, spliffs, beers, whatever it may be, we are all guilty of it and that‚Äôs not a bad thing as long as we are respectful. This is all good fun until it overflows into a popular trail. 

I want to take a second here to say I have nothing against perma rigs, I‚Äôve left lines up for close to a year in areas I‚Äôve helped establish. That being said, if you‚Äôre going to leave your hundreds or thousands of dollars of gear up in the mountains, particularly near a populated area, don‚Äôt be blown away when it gets taken or gets cut. These areas dont belong to us, we share them with the rest of the outdoor community and in most cases those communities (biking, running, climbing, backpacking) have been recreating in the areas we are longer than we have. Maybe it was the 70 year old man that‚Äôs been going to this trail for the last 50 years with his wife before highlines were even a blip on the radar? Stealing isn‚Äôt right but we need to consider how our actions have an impact on others and stop acting like brats when we can‚Äôt get away with doing whatever it is we want. It doesn‚Äôt matter if something is Open Space, National Forest or whatever it may be, the local governments can and will implement regulations on areas if we abuse our privileges to use these areas freely and have a negative impact. They have done it before and they will do it again. A lot of people act like they are entitled to these activities, like it‚Äôs owed to them. It‚Äôs not. The fact we have the freedom to do these things is beautiful but we need to understand it can be taken from us at any moment.

It‚Äôs amazing to have a permarig up and not have to rig, to be able to session solo and have that space to yourself. That‚Äôs a truly wonderful feeling and let‚Äôs be real, rigging isn‚Äôt the most fun, BUT we have to be aware of how this impacts others. There‚Äôs no denying a highline is kind of unsightly depending on where it‚Äôs rigged, obnoxious when it‚Äôs windy and honestly looks like an abandoned pile of shit hanging from the trees sometimes. People don‚Äôt leave mountain bikes piled at the trailhead because they don‚Äôt wanna lug them out the next day and then bitch if they get stolen. Same with climbing gear, someone may leave draws on a climb occasionally but they don‚Äôt leave all their ropes, cams and rack at the crag for a couple weeks and then show up in bewilderment when all their gear is gone. Ôøº

Again, I‚Äôm all for permarigs but respect, consideration, mindfulness and awareness surrounding our impact on the land we use and others using that land is going to preserve our access and relationships with land owners, law enforcement and fellow outdoor enthusiasts we share these areas with in the long run. Just don‚Äôt string a public place up for months on end and then throw a fit when your shit disappears. Make those rigs a little harder to get to and maybe a little, I don‚Äôt know, higher? üòò

topComments.name: Ryan Shute
topComments.text: One more thing: PUT YOUR CONTACT INFO ON YOUR PERMARIG!!! I don‚Äôt know why this hasn‚Äôt become a more common practice yet. It takes 5 minutes to go to the library, type, print and laminate a sign with your name and contact information on it for you to attach to your rig. I have had a few people contact me and ask about a rig I had up because my name and phone number was attached to the rig. This can be useful for several reasons.

topComments.name: Calvin Burghart
topComments.text:
I really appreciate this conversation. It's vital we have talk about this as the sport gets more popular. 
Nowadays climbing is considered a viable use of outdoor spaces, the same way fishing, rafting, hunting, etc. are. With that respect comes privileges like the opinions of the community in the sport being considered when governments decide what is allowed on public lands, but it wasnt always that way, they had to work long and hard (and establish ethical guidelines) in their respective communities.
In my opinion, we build that relationship by understanding and respecting the usage of the land by others (non-slackliners) in our communities. I've seen an attitude of disgruntlement or even distain towards our non-slackliner peers especially surrounding permarigs that worries me. There was an incident not long ago where climbers were using permarigs in my area as tyrolls to get across a dangerous river crossing. It was causing abrasion on the webbing and that was making slackliners in the community understandably upset, but take a moment to consider the point of view of those in the climbing community. There was no sign notifying them of what this thing was, it was located right next to a bunch of popular climbs in a high traffic area, it goes right over the water that everyone wants to cross, nobody responsible for this thing is anywhere around. It's an understandable conclusion that this is some sort of temperary or seasonal tyroll. Of course that's not what a highline is, and mistaking a highline for a tyroll can be very dangerous. To me this kind of situation highlights the disconnect between communities that leads to conflicts.
Signs go a long way, but we should still be constantly evaluating whether permarigs are in direct conflict with the larger community's use of public land. It sucks, especially as public spaces gain traffic; permarigs are awesome and we all love them, but they are literally plastic obstructions in natural spaces. At best they are unseen, at worst they are temperary littering.

I would recommend trying to first increase the size of your steps and then try to keep the steps that big and increase the speed. 
take some relatively static webbing and not too heavy, because when stepping next to the line the line will hit you in your balls, face or your arm. 
if you're on a highline make sure that someone is there who is able to rescue you, otherwise park might be even safer. And just speedwalk the part of the line where you're max 30cm above the ground. 
60m low-stretch light polyester I would say is perfect, but it doesn't matter too much.
